<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="340" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="3.[140,1108,307,827]" pageId="3" pageNumber="340">
This adventive Palearctic species has been recorded in 
<collectingCountry box="[815,901,448,474]" name="Canada" pageId="3" pageNumber="340">Canada</collectingCountry>
from 
<collectingRegion country="Canada" name="British Columbia" pageId="3" pageNumber="340">British Columbia</collectingRegion>
west to 
<collectingRegion box="[321,412,483,509]" country="Canada" name="Quebec" pageId="3" pageNumber="340">Québec</collectingRegion>
, Newfoundland, and 
<collectingRegion box="[665,804,483,510]" country="Canada" name="Nova Scotia" pageId="3" pageNumber="340">Nova Scotia</collectingRegion>
(
<bibRefCitation author="McNamara" box="[820,1021,483,509]" firstAuthor="McNamara" pageId="3" pageNumber="340" pagination="214 - 217" refId="ref11788" refString="McNamara J (1991) Family Nitidulidae: sap beetles. In: Bousquet Y (Ed) Checklist of Beetles of Canada and Alaska. Agriculture Canada Research Branch Publication 1861 / E.: 214 - 217." type="journal article" year="1991">McNamara 1991</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Majka and Cline" firstAuthor="Majka" pageId="3" pageNumber="340" pagination="314 - 332" refId="ref11619" refString="Majka CG, Cline AR (2006) Th e Nitidulidae and Kateretidae (Coleoptera) of Nova Scotia and Prince Edward Island. Th e Canadian Entomologist 138: 314 - 332." type="journal article" year="2006">Majka and Cline 2006</bibRefCitation>
), and in the 
<collectingCountry box="[464,615,518,545]" name="United States of America" pageId="3" pageNumber="340">United States</collectingCountry>
along the Atlantic seaboard south to 
<collectingRegion country="United States of America" name="North Carolina" pageId="3" pageNumber="340">North Carolina</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[297,412,554,580]" country="United States of America" name="Tennessee" pageId="3" pageNumber="340">Tennessee</collectingRegion>
, and west to 
<collectingRegion box="[569,672,554,580]" country="United States of America" name="Missouri" pageId="3" pageNumber="340">Missouri</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[685,743,554,580]" country="United States of America" name="Iowa" pageId="3" pageNumber="340">Iowa</collectingRegion>
, and 
<collectingRegion box="[807,930,554,580]" country="United States of America" name="Wisconsin" pageId="3" pageNumber="340">Wisconsin</collectingRegion>
. In the western 
<collectingCountry box="[140,295,589,615]" name="United States of America" pageId="3" pageNumber="340">United States</collectingCountry>
it has been found in 
<collectingRegion box="[556,666,589,615]" country="United States of America" name="Colorado" pageId="3" pageNumber="340">Colorado</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[680,820,589,615]" country="United States of America" name="Washington" pageId="3" pageNumber="340">Washington</collectingRegion>
, and 
<collectingRegion box="[888,1002,589,615]" country="United States of America" name="California" pageId="3" pageNumber="340">California</collectingRegion>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Parsons" firstAuthor="Parsons" pageId="3" pageNumber="340" pagination="121 - 278" refId="ref11921" refString="Parsons CT (1943) A revision of Nearctic Nitidulidae (Coleoptera). Bulletin of the Museum of Comparative Zoology 92: 121 - 278." type="journal article" year="1943">Parsons 1943</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Erichson" box="[225,413,624,650]" firstAuthor="Erichson" pageId="3" pageNumber="340" pagination="225 - 361" refId="ref10904" refString="Erichson WF (1843) Versuch einer systematischen Eintheilung der Nitidularien. Zeitschrift fur Entomologie 4: 225 - 361." type="journal article" year="1843">Erichson (1843)</bibRefCitation>
first recognized this species as occurring in the Nearctic by noting that the specimen sent to him from 
<collectingRegion box="[635,776,659,685]" country="United States of America" name="Connecticut" pageId="3" pageNumber="340">Connecticut</collectingRegion>
by Zimmerman was not different from specimens he possessed that originated from the Palearctic. This note likely was the basis for 
<bibRefCitation author="Melsheimer's" box="[328,552,729,756]" firstAuthor="Melsheimer's" pageId="3" pageNumber="340" pagination="98 - 118" refId="ref11828" refString="Melsheimer FE (1846) Descriptions of new species of Coleoptera of the United States. Proceedings of the Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia 2: 98 - 118." type="journal article" year="1846">Melsheimer’s (1846</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Melsheimer's" box="[563,623,729,756]" firstAuthor="Melsheimer's" pageId="3" pageNumber="340" refId="ref11859" refString="Melsheimer FE (1853) Catalogue of the described Coleoptera of the United States. Smithsonian Institution, Washington, D. C., 174 pp." type="book" year="1853">1853</bibRefCitation>
) record of the species. The common host is nettle (
<taxonomicName authorityName="C.Linnaeus" authorityYear="1753" box="[219,289,766,791]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Urticaceae" genus="Urtica" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="3" pageNumber="340" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[219,289,766,791]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="340">Urtica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spp., 
<taxonomicName authorityName="de Jussieu" authorityYear="1789" box="[353,473,765,792]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Urticaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="3" pageNumber="340" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Urticaceae</taxonomicName>
) (
<bibRefCitation author="Kirk-Spriggs" box="[493,705,765,792]" firstAuthor="Kirk-Spriggs" pageId="3" pageNumber="340" refId="ref11512" refString="Kirk-Spriggs AH (1996) Pollen Beetles, Coleoptera: Kateretidae and Nitidulidae: Meligethinae. Handbooks for the Identification of British Insects. Vol 5, Part 6 a. Royal Entomological Society of London, 157 pp." type="book" year="1996">Kirk-Spriggs 1996</bibRefCitation>
); however, it has been reported from elder (
<bibRefCitation author="Dillon and Dillon" box="[210,484,800,827]" firstAuthor="Dillon" pageId="3" pageNumber="340" refId="ref10816" refString="Dillon ES, Dillon LS (1961) A manual of common beetles of Eastern North America. Row, Peterson and Company, Evanston, 884 pp." type="book" year="1961">Dillon and Dillon 1961</bibRefCitation>
) and sifted from sphagnum moss (
<bibRefCitation author="Blatchley" box="[877,1053,800,826]" firstAuthor="Blatchley" pageId="3" pageNumber="340" refId="ref10578" refString="Blatchley WS (1910) The Coleoptera or beetles known to occur in Indiana. The Nature Publishing Co., Indianapolis, 1386 pp." type="book" year="1910">Blatchley 1910</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
